{"title_page": "Loring M. Black Jr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| name        = Loring Milton Black Jr.\n| image       = Loring M. Black.jpg\n| state      = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| district   = [[New York's 5th congressional district|5th]]\n| term_start = March 4, 1923\n| term_end   = January 3, 1935\n| preceded   = [[Ardolph L. Kline]]\n| succeeded  = [[Marcellus H. Evans]]\n| office1 = Member of the<br>[[New York Senate]]\n| constituency1 = [[New York's 4th State Senate district|4th district]]\n| term_start1   = January 1, 1911\n| term_end1     = December 31, 1912\n| preceded1     = Reuben L. Gledhill\n| succeeded1    = Henry P. Velte\n| constituency2 = [[New York's 6th State Senate district|6th district]]\n| term_start2   = January 1, 1919\n| term_end2     = December 31, 1920\n| preceded2     = [[Charles F. Murphy (Brooklyn)|Charles F. Murphy]]\n| succeeded2    = [[William T. Simpson]]\n\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date|May 17, 1886}}\n| death_date  = {{death-date and age|May 21, 1956|May 17, 1886}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]]\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| citizenship = {{US}}\n| spouse      = Beatrice M. Eddy Black\nLoy Spencer Black\n| children    =\n| profession  = [[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater  = \n| religion    = \n|}}\n'''Loring Milton Black Jr.''' (May 17, 1886  \u2013 May 21, 1956) was an [[United States|American]] politician and a [[United States Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was the son of Loring M. Black and Elizabeth Black, born on May 17, 1886, in [[New York City]]. He graduated from [[Fordham University]] in 1907. Then he studied law at [[Columbia Law School]], was admitted to the bar in 1909, and practiced in New York City. He was married to Beatrice M. Eddy, and later to Loy Spencer.\n\nBlack was a member of the [[New York State Senate]] (4th D.) in [[134th New York State Legislature|1911]] and [[135th New York State Legislature|1912]]. Due to his young age he became known as \"The Kid Senator\". He was again a member of the State Senate in [[142nd New York State Legislature|1919]] and [[143rd New York State Legislature|1920]].\n\nBlack was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[68th United States Congress|68th]], [[69th United States Congress|69th]], [[70th United States Congress|70th]], [[71st United States Congress|71st]], [[72nd United States Congress|72nd]] and [[73rd United States Congress]]es, holding office from March 4, 1923, to January 3, 1935. Opposing prohibition, he was one of the leaders of the \"wet bloc\" in Congress. Afterwards he resumed the practice of law in New York City and Washington, D.C.\n\nBlack died on May 21, 1956, in a drugstore at [[Washington, D.C.]], of a heart attack; and was buried at the Fort Lincoln Cemetery in [[Brentwood, Maryland]].\n\n==External links== \n{{CongBio|B000505}}\n*{{Find a Grave|15827317}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-sen}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Reuben L. Gledhill]] | title = [[New York State Senate]] <br>4th District | years = 1911\u20131912 | after = [[Henry P. Velte]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Charles F. Murphy (Brooklyn)|Charles F. Murphy]] | title = [[New York State Senate]] <br>6th District | years = 1919\u20131920 | after = [[William T. Simpson]]}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box | state = New York | district = 5 | before = [[Ardolph L. Kline]] | after = [[Marcellus H. Evans]] | years = 1923\u20131935}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Loring M. Jr.}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:New York state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Congressman\n| name        = Loring Milton Black Jr.\n| image       = Loring M. Black.jpg\n| state1      = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| district1   = [[New York's 5th congressional district|5th]]\n| term_start1 = March 4, 1923\n| term_end1   = January 3, 1935\n| preceded1   = [[Ardolph L. Kline]]\n| succeeded1  = [[Marcellus H. Evans]]\n| state_senate2= New York\n| district2= 6th\n| term_start2= January 1, 1919\n| term_end2= December 31, 1920\n| preceded2= [[Charles F. Murphy (Brooklyn)|Charles F. Murphy]]\n| succeeded2=[[William T. Simpson]]\n| state_senate3= New York\n| district3= 4th\n| term_start3= January 1, 1911\n| term_end3= December 31, 1912\n| preceded3= [[Reuben L. Gledhill]]\n| succeeded3=[[Henry P. Velte]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date|May 17, 1886}}\n| death_date  = {{death-date and age|May 21, 1956|May 17, 1886}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]]\n| death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| citizenship = {{US}}\n| spouse      = Beatrice M. Eddy Black\nLoy Spencer Black\n| children    =\n| profession  = [[Lawyer|Attorney]]\n| party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| alma_mater  = \n| religion    = \n|}}\n'''Loring Milton Black Jr.''' (May 17, 1886  \u2013 May 21, 1956) was an [[United States|American]] politician and a [[United States Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was the son of Loring M. Black and Elizabeth Black, born on May 17, 1886, in [[New York City]]. He graduated from [[Fordham University]] in 1907. Then he studied law at [[Columbia Law School]], was admitted to the bar in 1909, and practiced in New York City. He was married to Beatrice M. Eddy, and later to Loy Spencer.\n\nBlack was a member of the [[New York State Senate]] (4th D.) in [[134th New York State Legislature|1911]] and [[135th New York State Legislature|1912]]. Due to his young age he became known as \"The Kid Senator\". He was again a member of the State Senate in [[142nd New York State Legislature|1919]] and [[143rd New York State Legislature|1920]].\n\nBlack was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[68th United States Congress|68th]], [[69th United States Congress|69th]], [[70th United States Congress|70th]], [[71st United States Congress|71st]], [[72nd United States Congress|72nd]] and [[73rd United States Congress]]es, holding office from March 4, 1923, to January 3, 1935. Opposing prohibition, he was one of the leaders of the \"wet bloc\" in Congress. Afterwards he resumed the practice of law in New York City and Washington, D.C.\n\nBlack died on May 21, 1956, in a drugstore at [[Washington, D.C.]], of a heart attack; and was buried at the Fort Lincoln Cemetery in [[Brentwood, Maryland]].\n\n==External links== \n{{CongBio|B000505}}\n*{{Find a Grave|15827317}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-sen}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Reuben L. Gledhill]] | title = [[New York State Senate]] <br>4th District | years = 1911\u20131912 | after = [[Henry P. Velte]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Charles F. Murphy (Brooklyn)|Charles F. Murphy]] | title = [[New York State Senate]] <br>6th District | years = 1919\u20131920 | after = [[William T. Simpson]]}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box | state = New York | district = 5 | before = [[Ardolph L. Kline]] | after = [[Marcellus H. Evans]] | years = 1923\u20131935}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Loring M. Jr.}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fordham University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:New York state senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "-A-M-B-1996-", "label": "safe"